<h2 id="introduction">Introduction</h2>

<p>I previously created my portfolio site with Wordpress.  That site is still accessible at <a href="jasonmjam.wordpress.com">jasonmjam.wordpress.com</a>.</p>

<p>There are a number of benefits in creating a site with a powerful CMS like Wordpress, but I wanted to build a new site from scratch for a number of reasons:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Write in <a href="https://github.com/adam-p/markdown-here/wiki/Markdown-Cheatsheet">markdown</a> as widely as possible.  This includes when taking personal notes, writing documentation for work, and in this case, creating site content.  For many years Iâ€™ve had notes in all sorts of formats across different devices.  Itâ€™s been inefficient and a pain to unify.  Iâ€™d like to follow <a href="https://indieweb.org/">indieweb</a> principles.  With markdown, I own my content and formatting is (largely) universal.</li>
  <li>Create clean markdown copies of my past writing for archival purposes.</li>
  <li>Refresh my Sketch (and larger UI) chops.  I have been working a lot in Figma at work.  In another side project concurrent to this one, Iâ€™m learning Framer X.</li>
  <li>Learn CSS Grids.  See inspiration from <a href="https://ahmadnassri.com/">Ahmad Nassri</a> / <a href="https://twitter.com/meowlivia_/status/1116784686640979968">Olivia Ng</a></li>
  <li>Experiment with static site generators.</li>
  <li>Learn the <a href="https://jamstack.org/">JAMstack</a> a bit better after seeing my dev colleagues working in React and Gatsby.</li>
</ul>

<p>To view milestone accomplishments of the project and resources I found helpful during its creation, view the repositoryâ€™s <a href="README.MD">README.md</a>.</p>

